f the following maternal conditions most commonly causes intrauterine growth restriction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypertensive disorders","Gestational diabetes mellitus","Hypothyroidism","Iron deficiency anaemia","Multiple sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive disorders\u003C/strong\u003E during pregnancy, including pre-eclampsia and chronic hypertension, commonly cause intrauterine growth restriction by the reduction of uteroplacental blood flow and placental dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGestational diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E results in macrosomia (large for gestational age) rather than growth restriction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E, when treated appropriately during pregnancy, does not significantly impact fetal growth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, unless severe, rarely causes significant growth restriction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E does not directly affect fetal growth or placental function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important causes of intrauterine growth restriction include maternal smoking, malnutrition, infections, and fetal chromosomal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intrauterine growth restriction is defined as estimated fetal weight below the 10th percentile for gestational age.","Hypertensive disorders in pregnancy cause intrauterine growth restriction through reduced uteroplacental blood flow."],"references":["Sharma D, Shastri S, Sharma P. Intrauterine Growth Restriction: Antenatal and Postnatal Aspects. Clin Med Insights Pediatr. 2016 Jul 14;10:67-83. doi: 